<subsection xml:id="random-behavior">
<title>Random Behavior</title>

<p>The <c>Math.random()</c> method allows for interesting random behavior.</p>

<p>Using <c>Math.random()</c> in a condition allows something to happen a certain percentage of the time. For example, <c>if (Math.random() &lt; 0.10)</c> will cause something to happen 10% of the time. </p>


    <!--TODO: add choice questions-->

<p>Math.random() can also be used to generate a random number in a specific range. There are some important things to keep in mind.</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <p>
            <c>Math.random()</c> returns a random double (decimal) between 0 and 0.999999. It will never return 1. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <c>Math.random()*range</c> returns a random double between 0 and range, not including range.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <c>Math.random()*range + min</c> returns a random number from min to (min+range), exclusive.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <c>(int) (Math.random()*range + min)</c> returns a random integer from min to (min+range), exclusive.
        </p>
    </li>
</ul>

<!--TODO: add choice questions-->

<p>The 2024 FRQ Feeder uses random numbers in both of these ways to make interesting things happen.</p>

    </subsection>
